WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.170 --> 00:00:05.670
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:05.670 --> 00:00:06.950
AMY BLANKSON: Hey, everyone.

00:00:06.950 --> 00:00:08.491
Thank you so much
for having me here.

00:00:08.491 --> 00:00:11.360
This is such a privilege to get
to be your first speaker here

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.880
in this new, awesome
space and to get to spend

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:15.196
the afternoon with you.

00:00:15.196 --> 00:00:16.820
We're going to have
a lot of fun today.

00:00:16.820 --> 00:00:19.340
And I have a few
experiments up my sleeve

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:22.220
that I'm looking forward
to subjecting you to.

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:24.440
And I also have some
information that I really

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:26.810
am hoping to share and
convey to you, some of which

00:00:26.810 --> 00:00:29.600
you may already know
or you might already

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:31.252
feel validates who you are.

00:00:31.252 --> 00:00:32.960
And some of the
information which I think

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:35.150
might challenge you or
be great information

00:00:35.150 --> 00:00:38.060
to share with those of your
colleagues, friends, and family

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:41.280
members who weren't
able to be here today.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:43.910
So I want to start off
with one statement that's

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:46.070
really beginning to challenge.

00:00:46.070 --> 00:00:48.260
It was the beginning
and the genesis

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:49.970
of what caused me
to write my book

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:51.380
on "The Future of Happiness."

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:53.360
And it was a statement
I read that said,

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:56.720
technology is the greatest
disruptor of happiness

00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:59.270
in human history.

00:00:59.270 --> 00:01:01.230
And is that really true?

00:01:01.230 --> 00:01:04.040
We hear news from
multiple different sources

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:07.740
about how technology is the
equivalent of digital heroin.

00:01:07.740 --> 00:01:10.700
How there is screen
time that's eroding

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:13.490
the fabric of our society
and ruining our relationships

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:15.755
with our grandparents.

00:01:15.755 --> 00:01:17.660
But some of this
information comes

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:19.400
from a sensationalized source.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:22.640
And so I wanted to delve into,
what is the truth about this?

00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:25.070
I come from a background in
positive psychology, which

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:27.050
is an odd place to
come to technology.

00:01:27.050 --> 00:01:29.810
Most people think that
technology and happiness

00:01:29.810 --> 00:01:32.152
are actually oxymorons.

00:01:32.152 --> 00:01:33.860
But I think that
there's something really

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:35.990
important to be said for
the time and the place

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:38.270
that we're living in
that requires us to think

00:01:38.270 --> 00:01:40.520
a little bit more
deeply about how we're

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:42.290
living in the digital age.

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:45.830
How can we live with greater
happiness and mindfulness

00:01:45.830 --> 00:01:46.640
in the digital age?

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:49.730
Is this even possible, or is
it truly the greatest disrupter

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:51.980
of happiness in human history?

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:54.080
In the past 10
years, we have found

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:57.920
that technology has sped up
so dramatically that we find

00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:01.610
ourselves overwhelmed and
unprepared for the challenges

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:02.990
that we face today.

00:02:02.990 --> 00:02:06.620
We find that since the
iPhone came out in 2007,

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:09.289
we're now about a decade
out from the first iPhone,

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:11.580
that the world has
changed dramatically.

00:02:11.580 --> 00:02:14.540
We have technology that
would have blown our minds 10

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:18.290
years ago, from FaceTime
to 3D printed organs that

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:19.610
are saving lives.

00:02:19.610 --> 00:02:22.490
And yet at the same time, we're
finding that depression rates

00:02:22.490 --> 00:02:24.960
have doubled in that
same period of time,

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.670
that the amount of cyberbullying
has gone up by 88% just

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:31.430
in the last five years
alone, and that the number

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:34.490
of repetitive stress injuries
for teenagers visiting

00:02:34.490 --> 00:02:36.920
the chiropractor-- teenagers--

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:39.500
have gone up by 50%.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:41.234
That's from a lot of this.

00:02:41.234 --> 00:02:42.650
And I think that
it's interesting,

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:45.260
and it's changing the way
that we're thinking about how

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:46.970
are we as a society evolving?

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:50.510
What does that mean for us,
not only physiologically,

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:52.220
but also emotionally.

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:54.450
What is this doing
to our happiness?

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:55.760
Now don't be alarmed.

00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:56.990
I know I'm in a tech space.

00:02:56.990 --> 00:02:57.942
I love Google.

00:02:57.942 --> 00:02:59.900
And I think that it's
important to reassure you

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:02.474
that I'm not anti-tech,
that I'm also not going

00:03:02.474 --> 00:03:03.890
to tell you that
you need to throw

00:03:03.890 --> 00:03:05.390
your phones out the window.

00:03:05.390 --> 00:03:07.710
I'm actually a huge
fan of technology.

00:03:07.710 --> 00:03:09.950
I believe it has
so much potential.

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:11.810
But part of my
mission and my message

00:03:11.810 --> 00:03:15.020
is to help us use technology
in our personal lives,

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:17.300
as well as their
professional lives, in a way

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:19.820
that fosters mindfulness,
in a way that

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:22.760
elevates our emotional
well-being and our happiness

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:23.489
for the long run.

00:03:23.489 --> 00:03:26.030
Because I believe that the path
that we are setting ourselves

00:03:26.030 --> 00:03:28.700
on right now, right
here today, is

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:31.160
what's going to determine
how we feel in the future

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.590
and what our world
looks like today.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:36.440
Currently, what we struggle
with is overwhelming

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:37.760
social media feed.

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:39.470
We have news coming
from all sources.

00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:41.480
Our Twitter feed is
constantly coming in.

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:43.647
You've got e-mails that
are probably piling up

00:03:43.647 --> 00:03:45.980
while you listen to me talk
about not being stressed out

00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:46.563
by technology.

00:03:46.563 --> 00:03:47.075
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:47.075 --> 00:03:49.130
And you have to go back
and answer all of them.

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:54.094
We have Netflix feeds that are
now creating a backlog of shows

00:03:54.094 --> 00:03:55.760
that we're going to
have to catch up on,

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:57.920
because they're releasing
all the episodes at once.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:00.080
And these things begin
to stress us out,

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:02.450
even though they're things
that make us happy, even

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:03.866
though they're
things are supposed

00:04:03.866 --> 00:04:05.540
to drive our productivity.

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:08.120
We find ourselves feeling
more and more overwhelmed,

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:10.430
frustrated, and
unprepared for how

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:13.492
to deal with the onslaught
of information in our lives.

00:04:13.492 --> 00:04:15.200
So the question that
I want to pose today

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.720
is, can our happiness
and our health

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:20.870
keep pace with the
speed of innovation?

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:22.370
And I think that
the question really

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:25.430
comes down to a bit of
self-awareness on our own part.

00:04:25.430 --> 00:04:28.850
Oftentimes we'll feel like
victims of distraction,

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:32.010
that somebody keeps texting you
when you're trying to focus,

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:34.430
that so and so keeps
sending your messages

00:04:34.430 --> 00:04:37.070
that you don't care about,
that you're getting bulk email

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:39.740
messages or junk mail or
junk phone calls that you

00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:41.340
have to deal with.

00:04:41.340 --> 00:04:43.740
But the truth is that
sometimes we actually

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:47.150
invite those distractions
into our lives.

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:49.436
How many times have you
ever been in a conversation

00:04:49.436 --> 00:04:50.810
with a friend
where you're having

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:54.140
this really deep, important
conversation, and all

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:56.056
of a sudden you hear
a beep, and they say,

00:04:56.056 --> 00:04:57.180
oh, excuse me for a minute.

00:04:57.180 --> 00:04:59.630
I got to get out my phone
and check this message.

00:04:59.630 --> 00:05:02.630
And your moment of
quality time is lost.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:04.650
Those moments
happen all the time.

00:05:04.650 --> 00:05:06.260
And get a load of this--

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:07.670
there was a survey
done recently,

00:05:07.670 --> 00:05:10.610
a national survey of smartphone
users, that asked people

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:13.310
how often it's OK to
pick up their phone.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:15.170
And not surprisingly,
about half of people

00:05:15.170 --> 00:05:17.419
said it was OK to pick up
their phone during dinner.

00:05:17.419 --> 00:05:19.710
About half the people-- it's
a little more surprising--

00:05:19.710 --> 00:05:23.250
say that they will pick up
their phone in the bathroom.

00:05:23.250 --> 00:05:26.360
Get this, a third of
people, a third of people

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:28.880
said it's OK to pick up
their phone during sex.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.130
I think this is the moment
in which I realized, OK, we

00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:32.120
have a problem.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:34.800
We've got to talk about this.

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.300
There's something
going on where we

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:39.430
feel like we need to be
needed, where it feels so good,

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:41.550
and so addictive,
other people find

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:45.240
our attention valuable, that
they need to constantly come

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:46.080
after us.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:49.110
And there's a reason why we
continue to feed into it.

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:52.410
So what is that, and what is it
doing to our emotional state?

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:55.500
What I find happening, from a
positive psychology standpoint,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.060
is that so often we are chasing
after this emotional high

00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:01.440
that we are literally running
ourselves off of what I

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:03.250
call the happiness cliff.

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:04.890
And the happiness
cliff is that moment

00:06:04.890 --> 00:06:07.230
when you are surfing
your Facebook feed,

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:09.870
and you're really enjoying
connecting with your friends

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:10.900
and your family members.

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.180
Seeing oh, that cute
kid just started school.

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:15.180
And oh, this really
important article

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:17.250
just came out that I
need to check in on.

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:20.070
About 30 minutes in,
you're still surfing,

00:06:20.070 --> 00:06:21.600
and you don't even know why.

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:24.960
An hour, an hour and
a half, there you are.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:26.730
And what happens
is that we cross

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:31.050
the point of what I call the
point of diminishing return,

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:33.180
which is that point
at which we passed

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:35.850
our maximum utility
for using technology

00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:39.226
to increase our productivity,
and then we went off the edge.

00:06:39.226 --> 00:06:41.350
So that point, actually,
if you look at this graph,

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:43.183
it's really interesting
to me that the point

00:06:43.183 --> 00:06:46.890
of highest productivity comes
before the peak of the curve.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:48.840
But the point at
which people realize

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:50.530
that they've fallen
off the cliff

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:53.320
is way on the other
side of the curve.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:55.680
So what I'm going to do is
to help you think through

00:06:55.680 --> 00:06:59.100
how do I recognize both,
in terms of emotion

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:01.080
and through my
physical body, how

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:04.590
do I recognize that point
of maximum productivity,

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.230
and then be able to
train myself to stop

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:09.330
before I fall off the cliff?

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:11.010
And that's a skill
set that I think

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:13.515
that we're just now beginning
to develop and emerge with.

00:07:13.515 --> 00:07:15.390
Because these are
challenges that we've never

00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:16.820
had to deal with before.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:19.560
We're in an area where
we've never had boundaries

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:21.360
that we had to create for this.

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:24.170
And all of a sudden, we as
a society are recognizing,

00:07:24.170 --> 00:07:26.490
OK, I think it might be
time for some boundaries.

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:27.480
I feel that.

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.230
I just don't know
what to do about it.

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:31.830
So what I want to do is to
bring you to positive psychology

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:34.620
and some of the time tested
strategies and principles

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:36.275
that we learned from
the field that I

00:07:36.275 --> 00:07:39.360
think can be really, really
helpful to understanding what's

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:41.040
going on in your
own mind and body

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:42.850
and what you can do about it.

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:45.099
So how many of you
grew up in the '80s?

00:07:45.099 --> 00:07:46.890
Raise your hand if you
grew up in the '80s.

00:07:46.890 --> 00:07:49.740
Then you might be familiar
with this old ad that used

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:51.540
to be part of the war on drugs.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:53.020
It said this is your brain.

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:54.454
This is your brain on drugs.

00:07:54.454 --> 00:07:55.370
This is my take on it.

00:07:55.370 --> 00:07:58.380
This is your brain on too much
technology, where you literally

00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:01.710
have fried it by letting it sit
on your computer for too long.

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:04.200
So that's the mental
image of what happens.

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:06.810
I also like to use the
analogy of a sunburn.

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:09.300
And a lot of people say,
well, how long would

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:12.030
you recommend that people
should be on computers?

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.130
Like, the American
Academy of Pediatrics

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:17.460
now advises or used to
advise that children

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:20.730
between the ages of two and ten
spent no more than two hours

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:22.050
on computers a day.

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:23.850
And over time, they
started to change that.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:26.560
Well, you know if they're in
school that doesn't count.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.400
Or if they're talking to family
members, that doesn't count.

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:31.860
What we're finding is there's
a lot of gray area in there

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:35.429
for what is acceptable
for time on the computer.

00:08:35.429 --> 00:08:38.820
And not everybody hits the point
of frying upon their computer

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:39.979
at the same point.

00:08:39.979 --> 00:08:41.520
Just in the same
way that some people

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.480
sunburn at different rates.

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:44.570
My skin is pretty fair.

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:47.310
I know I sunburn pretty much
every time I walk outside.

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:48.900
My husband has a
much darker skin,

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:50.889
and he can handle
a lot more sun.

00:08:50.889 --> 00:08:52.680
But what's happened
over time is we've both

00:08:52.680 --> 00:08:53.638
learned our own bodies.

00:08:53.638 --> 00:08:55.980
We know that I have
to use sunscreen.

00:08:55.980 --> 00:08:57.900
I know when I'm feeling
burned and that it's

00:08:57.900 --> 00:08:58.990
time to deal with it.

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:01.323
And my husband knows that he
can just go outside and not

00:09:01.323 --> 00:09:02.910
even have to worry about it.

00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:05.310
Those biological
symptoms become so

00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:08.190
crucial to shaping
my behavior, changing

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:11.910
what I'm doing with by
preventative measures

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:14.106
as well as recognizing
signs and symptoms.

00:09:14.106 --> 00:09:15.480
And so I think
what we need to do

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:17.580
is start recognizing,
when does our egg start

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:18.930
frying on the laptop?

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:20.050
What is that point?

00:09:20.050 --> 00:09:23.340
And how do we get away from
it when we hit that point?

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:25.480
You might think well,
what's so bad about it.

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:27.780
I mean, I might play around
the edges a little bit

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:29.060
now and then.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:31.510
I might even have to be
on my computer for work.

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:33.930
So I can't cut
back on the amount

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:35.900
of time I'm on the screen.

00:09:35.900 --> 00:09:38.400
Let me share with you the impact
or destruction in our lives

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:41.020
that's emerge, in
the past 10 years.

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:43.800
In the year 2013, The
National Information Center

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:47.160
for Biotechnology reported
that the human attention span

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:50.859
has now dropped below
that of a goldfish,

00:09:50.859 --> 00:09:51.900
below that of a goldfish.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:54.570
A goldfish's attention
span is nine seconds,

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:57.140
and a human attention
span is now eight seconds.

00:09:57.140 --> 00:09:59.940
Now just let that
sink in for a moment.

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:00.917
It's crazy.

00:10:00.917 --> 00:10:01.625
What that means--

00:10:01.625 --> 00:10:02.249
[PIANO PLAYING]

00:10:02.249 --> 00:10:03.390
--for us-- whoops.

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:04.681
Let me pause that for a second.

00:10:05.786 --> 00:10:08.017
Talk about distraction.

00:10:08.017 --> 00:10:09.600
What that means for
us is that there's

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:11.490
some really key
information for us

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:13.560
that we need to
process about what that

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:15.160
means when we get distracted.

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:18.240
And so to show you what
distraction does to our mind,

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:19.980
I want to show you
this two minute clip.

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:21.540
It's really fun
and entertaining,

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:24.240
and it'll give you a snippet of
an idea about what destruction

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:24.930
does to us.

